Objective:
Simulate a real attack from Kali Linux against Windows Server and detect it in Splunk using Windows Security logs.

Enabled RDP on Windows Server
RDP was not enabled by default on Windows Server 2022. Enabled it first.

Simulated Failed Logins from Windows 11
Before attacking from Kali, tested the detection:
Connected to Windows Server via Remote Desktop Connection from Windows 11
Deliberately entered wrong credentials 6 times
Confirmed EventCode=4625 (failed logon) appeared in Splunk 

This confirmed the full pipeline was working :
Failed login → Windows Security Log → Universal Forwarder → Splunk

Brute Force Attack from Kali
Ran a brute force attack against Windows Server RDP from Kali Linux using Hydra and the rockyou.txt wordlist.
First had to extract the wordlist :
bashsudo gunzip /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt.gz
Then launched the attack :
bashhydra -l Administrator -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt rdp://192.168.10.1

Detection in Splunk
Searched for failed logon events in Splunk :
index=* sourcetype="WinEventLog:Security" EventCode=4625 (prompt provided by Claude)
Results showed multiple EventCode=4625 events from the attacker IP (192.168.10.101) hitting DC01 in succession.
Source_Network_Address : 192.168.10.101 (Kali)
Account_Name : Administrator (targeted account)
Failure_Reason : Unknown username or bad password


